{{short description|People from Afghanistan}} {{about||the historical ethnic group|Afghan (ethnonym)|other uses of the term|Afghan (disambiguation)}}
'''Afghan'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.macmillandictionary.com/dictionary/british/afghanistani|title=Afghanistani (noun) definition and synonyms {{!}} Macmillan Dictionary|website=www.macmillandictionary.com|language=en|access-date=2018-10-24}}</ref> ([[Pashto language|Pashto]]/{{lang-fa|افغان}}; see: ''[[Afghan (ethnonym)|etymology]]'') refers to someone or something from [[Afghanistan]], in particular a citizen of that country.<ref>{{Cite book|author =Garner, Bryan |year=2009 |title=Garner's Modern American Usage |edition=third|location=New York |publisher=Oxford University Press |page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=FwmQpyibKkAC&pg=PA27 27] |isbn=978-0-19-538275-4}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|author1=Siegal, Allan M. |author2=Connolly, William |year=2015 |title=The New York Times Manual of Style and Usage |edition=fifth |location=New York |publisher=Crown Publishing Group |page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=o2E5BgAAQBAJ&pg=PT18 18] |isbn=978-1-336-02484-7}}</ref> Prior to the rise of the nation as Afghanistan, it was used by [[Persian language|Persian speakers]] and those influenced by the Persian language to denote the [[Pashtun people]]. In modern times, '''Afghan''' is rarely used as an ethnic term for the [[Pashtun People|Pashtuns]], but is rather used as the national [[demonym]] for all citizens of Afghanistan<ref>In referring to the former usage of "Afghan" as synonymous with "Pashtun", Maley said, ''While this was certainly the sense in which the word 'Afghan' was used in major nineteenth-century works (and continues to be used in parts of Afghanistan), such usage has now almost completely died out in English-language sources.'' {{Cite book|author =Maley, William |year=2009 |title=The Afghanistan Wars |edition=second |location=[[Basingstoke]], England |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=6OMcBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA8 8] |isbn=978-0-230-21313-5}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|author =Naby, Eden |year=1988 |chapter=The Changing Role of Islam as a Unifying Force in Afghanistan |editor1=Banuazizi, Ali |editor2=Weiner, Myron |title=The State, Religion, and Ethnic Politics: Afghanistan, Iran, and Pakistan |location=Syracuse, New York |publisher=Syracuse University Press |pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=l6cmuTfzvZEC&pg=PA124 124–154] |isbn=978-0-8156-2448-6}}</ref>—[[Pashtun People|Pashtuns]], and many [[Tajik people|Tajiks]], [[Hazara people|Hazaras]], [[Uzbek people|Uzbeks]], [[Aimaq people|Aimaqs]], [[Turkmen people|Turkmens]], [[Baloch people|Balochs]], [[Nuristani people|Nuristanis]], [[Pashayi people|Pashayis]], [[Pamiri people|Pamiris]], [[History of Arabs in Afghanistan|Arabs]], and others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.umsl.edu/services/govdocs/wofact92/wf930006.txt |author=Central Intelligence Agency|title=Afghanistan: People |work=The World Factbook |publisher=University of Missouri|date=22 January 1993|accessdate=20 December 2015}}</ref> According to the ''[[Encyclopædia Iranica]]'', the word Afghan (afḡān) in current political usage means any citizen of Afghanistan, regardless of their tribal or religious affiliation.<ref>{{cite web |work=[[Encyclopædia Iranica]] |title=AFGHAN|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/afgan-in-current-political-usage-any-citizen-of-afghanistan-whatever-his-ethnic-tribal-or-religious-affiliation}}</ref> According to the [[1964 Afghanistan Constitution|1964 Constitution of Afghanistan]], all Afghans are equal in rights and obligations before the law.<ref>{{cite web|title=Article 1 of the 1964 Constitution of Afghanistan|url=http://www.afghan-web.com/history/const/const1964.html|publisher=Government of Afghanistan|accessdate=June 13, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110917002320/http://www.afghan-web.com/history/const/const1964.html|archive-date=2011-09-17|url-status=dead}}</ref> The fourth article of the current [[Constitution of Afghanistan]] states that citizens of Afghanistan consist of [[Pashtun people|Pashtun]], [[Tajik people|Tajik]], [[Hazara people|Hazara]], [[Uzbeks|Uzbek]], [[Turkmen people|Turkmen]], [[Aimaq people|Aimaq]], [[History of Arabs in Afghanistan|Arab]], [[Baloch people|Baluch]], [[Pashai people|Pashayi]], [[Nuristani people|Nuristani]], [[Qizilbash]], [[Gurjar people|Gurjar]], [[Brahui people|Brahui]], and members of other tribes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Constitution of Afghanistan|url=http://www.embassyofafghanistan.org/page/constitution |quote=National sovereignty in Afghanistan shall belong to the nation, manifested directly and through its elected representatives. The nation of Afghanistan is composed of all individuals who possess the citizenship of Afghanistan. The nation of Afghanistan shall be {{sic|comprised |hide=y|of}} Pashtun, Tajik, Hazara, Uzbek, Turkman, Baluch, Pachaie, Nuristani, Aymaq, Arab, Qirghiz, Qizilbash, Gujur, Brahwui and other tribes. The word Afghan shall apply to every citizen of Afghanistan. No individual of the nation of Afghanistan shall be deprived of citizenship. The citizenship and asylum related matters shall be regulated by law.|year=2004 |accessdate=2013-02-16}}</ref>
As an adjective, the word Afghan also means "of or relating to Afghanistan or its people, [[pashto|language]], or culture".
==Afghani== The term "Afghani" refers to the unit of [[Afghan afghani|Afghan currency]]. The term is also often used (and appears in some dictionaries) for a person or thing related to Afghanistan, although some have expressed the opinion that this usage is incorrect.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chatterbox: More on 'Afghani' |url=http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/chatterbox/2001/10/more_on_afghani.html |website=[[Slate.com|Slate]] |date=October 4, 2001 |accessdate=March 29, 2013}}</ref> The term "Afghani" (or more usually "al-Afghani") is also a common surname among Afghans – for example, [[Jamāl al-Dīn al-Afghānī]] and [[Jamila Afghani]].
The Afghani currency unit was created in 1925. Between 1925 and 1993 varieties of Afghani coins and banknotes were in circulation through Afghanistan. Coins issued during this period consisted of: 1, 2, 3, 5, 10, 20, 25 [[Pul (coin)|pul]] in bronze, brass, copper nickel, and aluminum-bronze; silver ½, 1, and 2½ Afghani; and gold ½, 1, and 2½ amani. Banknotes issued were in: 2, 5, 10, 20, 50, 100, 500, 1,000, 5,000, and 10,000 Afghani. In 1958 bank notes worth 2 and 5 were switched with coins.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://famouswonders.com/afghan-afghani/|title=Afghan Afghani|work=famouswonders.com}}</ref>
